Exercise 2

We have seen that in \(p = 2\) dimensions, a linear decision boundary takes the form \(\beta_0 + \beta_1X_1 + \beta_2X_2 = 0\). We now investigate a non-linear decision boundary.

  1. Sketch the curve \[(1 + X_1)^2 + (2 X_2 )^2 = 4.\]

  2. On your sketch, indicate the set of points for which \[(1 + X_1)^2 + (2 X_2)^2 > 4,\] as well as the set of points for which \[(1 + X_1)^2 + (2 X_2)^2 \le 4.\]

  3. Suppose that a classifier assigns an observation to the blue class if \[(1 + X_1)^2 + (2 X_2)^2 > 4,\] and to the red class otherwise. To what class is the observation \((0, 0)\) classified? \((1, 1)\)? \((2, 2)\)? \((3, 8)\)?

  4. Argue that while the decision boundary in (c) is not linear in terms of \(X_1\) and \(X_2\), it is linear in terms of \(X_1\), \(X_1^2\), \(X_2\), and \(X_2^2\).

Preliminaries:

This decision boundary is a circle with equation: \[ \left(1+X_{1}\right)^{2}+\left(2-X_{2}\right)^{2}=4 \]

The center is \((-1, 2)\), the radius is 2.

(a)

# https://stackoverflow.com/a/6863490
circleFun <- function(center = c(0,0),diameter = 1, npoints = 100){
    r = diameter / 2
    tt <- seq(0,2*pi,length.out = npoints)
    xx <- center[1] + r * cos(tt)
    yy <- center[2] + r * sin(tt)
    return(data.frame(X1 = xx, X2 = yy))
}

curve <- circleFun(c(-1, 2), 4, npoints = 1000)

ggplot() +
  geom_path(data = curve, aes(X1, X2)) +
  theme_bw() +
  labs(x = TeX("X_1"), y = TeX("X_2"),
       title = TeX("(1 + X_1)^2 + (2  X_2 )^2 = 4")) +
  coord_fixed()

(b)

grid <- expand.grid(seq(-4, 4, by = 0.01), seq(-1, 10, by = 0.01))
names(grid) <- c("X1", "X2")
grid$class <- (1 + grid$X1)^2 + (2 - grid$X2)^2 > 4

p1 <- ggplot(grid, aes(X1, X2)) +
  geom_raster(data = grid, aes(X1, X2, fill = class), alpha = 0.6) +
  scale_x_continuous(limits = c(-4, 2), expand = c(0, 0)) +
  scale_y_continuous(limits = c(-1, 5), expand = c(0, 0)) +
  geom_hline(aes(yintercept = 0), color = "grey50") + # x-axis
  geom_vline(aes(xintercept = 0), color = "grey50") + # y-axis
  labs(x = TeX("X_1"), y = TeX("X_2")) +
  scale_fill_discrete(TeX("$(1 + X_1)^2 + (2 - X_2)^2 > 4$")) +
  theme_bw() +
  coord_fixed()
p1

(c)

\((0, 0)\), \((2, 2)\) and \((3, 8)\) are in the blue class. \((-1, 1)\) is in the red class.

(d)

\[ \left(1+X_{1}\right)^{2}+\left(2-X_{2}\right)^{2}=4 \] \[ \left(1+2X_{1} + X_1^2\right) + \left(4 - 4X_{2} + X_2^2\right) = 4 \] \[ X_1^2 + X_2^2 + 2X_{1} - 4X_{2} + 1 = 0 \] \[ aX_1^2 + bX_2^2 + cX_{1} + dX_{2} + e = 0, \] where \[ a = 1;~ b = 1;~ c = 2;~ d = -4;~ e = 1 \] Rewriting the equation for the decision boundary in the above form shows that it can be written as a linear combination of \(X_{1}\), \(X_{1}^{2}\), \(X_{2}\), and \(X_{2}^{2}\).

Exercise 3

Here we explore the maximal margin classifier on a toy data set.

  1. We are given \(n = 7\) observations in \(p = 2\) dimensions. For each observation, there is an associated class label. \[ \begin{array}{rlll}{\text { Obs. }} & {X_{1}} & {X_{2}} & {Y} \\ \hline 1 & {3} & {4} & {\text { Red }} \\ {2} & {2} & {2} & {\text { Red }} \\ {3} & {4} & {4} & {\text { Red }} \\ {4} & {1} & {4} & {\text { Red }} \\ {5} & {2} & {1} & {\text { Blue }} \\ {6} & {4} & {3} & {\text { Blue }} \\ {7} & {4} & {1} & {\text { Blue }} \\ \hline\end{array} \] Sketch the observations.
  2. Sketch the optimal separating hyperplane, and provide the equation for this hyperplane (of the form (9.1)).
  3. Describe the classification rule for the maximal margin classifier. It should be something along the lines of Classify to Red if \(\beta_0 + \beta_1X_1 + \beta_2X_2 > 0\), and classify to Blue otherwise. Provide the values for \(\beta_0\), \(\beta_1\), and \(\beta_2\).
  4. On your sketch, indicate the margin for the maximal margin hyperplane.
  5. Indicate the support vectors for the maximal margin classifier.
  6. Argue that a slight movement of the seventh observation would not affect the maximal margin hyperplane.
  7. Sketch a hyperplane that is not the optimal separating hyperplane, and provide the equation for this hyperplane.
  8. Draw an additional observation on the plot so that the two classes are no longer separable by a hyperplane.

(a)

df <- data.frame(X1 = c(3, 2, 4, 1, 2, 4, 4),
                 X2 = c(4, 2, 4, 4, 1, 3, 1),
                 Y =  c("Red", "Red", "Red", "Red", "Blue", "Blue", "Blue"))

cols <- c("Red" = "#F8766D", "Blue" = "#619CFF")
ggplot(df) +
  geom_point(aes(X1, X2, color = Y), size = 2) +
  scale_color_manual(values = cols) +
  theme_bw() +
  guides(color = guide_legend(reverse = TRUE))

(b)

The points \((2, 1.5)\) and \((4, 3.5)\) are half way between the two pairs of closest points from each class. The optimal hyperplane will intersect these two points. The slope of this line (\(m\)) is:

\[ m = \frac{y_2 - y_1}{x_2 - x_1} \] \[ m = \frac{3.5 - 1.5}{4 - 2} \] \[ m = 1 \]

The \(y\)-intercept (or \(X2\)-intercept), \(y_0\), is: \[ y_0 = y - mx \] Sub in \(m\) and the values for one of the points, \((2, 1.5)\):

\[ \begin{aligned} y_0 &= (1.5) - (1)(2) \\ y_0 &= -0.5 \end{aligned} \]

Using these values for \(m\) and \(y_0\) we can add the line to the plot:

ggplot(df) +
  geom_point(aes(X1, X2, color = Y), size = 2) +
  geom_abline(aes(slope = 1, intercept = -0.5)) +
  scale_color_manual(values = cols) +
  theme_bw() +
  guides(color = guide_legend(reverse = TRUE))

We require the equation of the hyperplane in the below form. \[ \beta_{0}+\beta_{1} X_{1}+\beta_{2} X_{2}=0 \hspace{2cm} (9.1) \]

We can rewrite our above equation in terms of \(\beta\)-coefficients and \(X_1\) and \(X_2\):

\[ y_0 + mx - y = 0 \equiv \beta_{0}+\beta_{1} X_{1}+\beta_{2} X_{2}=0, \] where \[ \begin{aligned} \beta_0 &= y_0 = -0.5, \\ \beta_1 &= m = 1, \\ \beta_2 &= -1 . \end{aligned} \]

This gives us our equation of the hyperplane: \[ -0.5 + X_1 - X_2 = 0 \]

(c)

Classify to Red if \(-0.5 + X_1 - X_2 > 0\), classify to Blue otherwise.

(d)

The margins for the maximal margin hyperplane will intersect the points closest to the hyperplane. The margins have the same slope, \(m\), as the hyperplane. The intercepts are \((2) - (1)(2) = 0\) for the margin that goes through \((2, 2)\), and \((1) - (1)(2) = -1\) for the margin that goes through \((2, 1)\):

ggplot(df) +
  geom_point(aes(X1, X2, color = Y), size = 2) +
  geom_abline(aes(slope = 1, intercept = -0.5)) +
  geom_abline(aes(slope = 1, intercept = 0), color = "#F8766D", linetype = "dashed") +
  geom_abline(aes(slope = 1, intercept = -1), color = "#619CFF", linetype = "dashed") +
  scale_color_manual(values = cols) +
  theme_bw() +
  guides(color = guide_legend(reverse = TRUE))

(e)

The support vectors are marked on the plot with an x:

df$support <- c(FALSE, TRUE, TRUE, FALSE, TRUE, TRUE, FALSE)
shapes <- c(20, 4)

ggplot(df) +
  geom_point(aes(X1, X2, color = Y, shape = support), size = 3) +
  geom_abline(aes(slope = 1, intercept = -0.5)) +
  geom_abline(aes(slope = 1, intercept = 0), color = "#F8766D", linetype = "dashed") +
  geom_abline(aes(slope = 1, intercept = -1), color = "#619CFF", linetype = "dashed") +
  scale_color_manual(values = cols) +
  scale_shape_manual(values = shapes) +
  theme_bw() +
  guides(color = guide_legend(reverse = TRUE)) #+  guides(shape = guide_legend(legend.position = "none"))

(f)

The seventh observation, \((4, 1)\), is not a support vector, and can move anywhere within the blue shaded region without having an effect on the maximal margin hyperplane:

grid <- expand.grid(seq(0, 5, by = 0.01), seq(0, 5, by = 0.01))
names(grid) <- c("X1", "X2")
grid$region <- (-1 + grid$X1 - grid$X2 > 0)

tiles <- c(NA, '#619CFF')
ggplot(df) +
  geom_tile(data = grid, aes(X1, X2, fill = region), alpha = 0.3) +
  scale_fill_manual(name = "Region of No Effect", values = tiles) +
  geom_point(aes(X1, X2, color = Y, shape = support), size = 3) +
  geom_abline(aes(slope = 1, intercept = -0.5)) +
  geom_abline(aes(slope = 1, intercept = 0), color = "#F8766D", linetype = "dashed") +
  geom_abline(aes(slope = 1, intercept = -1), color = "#619CFF", linetype = "dashed") +
  scale_color_manual(values = cols) +
  scale_shape_manual(values = shapes) +
  scale_x_continuous(expand = c(0, 0)) +
  scale_y_continuous(expand = c(0, 0)) +
  theme_bw() +
  guides(color = guide_legend(reverse = TRUE)) #+ #guides(shape = guide_legend(legend.position = "none"))

(g)

Any line that is not the hyperplane we have drawn will be suboptimal. Draw a line with the same slope but a different \(y\)-intercept of 1, whose equation is \(1 + X_1 - X_2 = 0\):

ggplot(df) +
  geom_point(aes(X1, X2, color = Y), size = 2) +
  geom_abline(aes(slope = 1, intercept = 1)) +
  scale_color_manual(values = cols) +
  theme_bw() +
  guides(color = guide_legend(reverse = TRUE))

We can see that this line no longer separates the observations by class.

(h)

An additional point that falls on the far side of the margin opposite to that of its class will mean the data is no longer separable by a hyperplane. Add a new observation so that it falls into the red region defined by the hyperplane in the above plots, but which is assigned a class of Blue:

df[nrow(df) + 1, ] <- c(2, 3, "Blue", FALSE)

ggplot(df) +
  geom_point(aes(X1, X2, color = Y), size = 2) +
  scale_color_manual(values = cols) +
  theme_bw() +
  guides(color = guide_legend(reverse = TRUE))

Now the data can no longer be separated by a hyperplane.
